Fu Jian wanted to bring Kumarajiva to China. When he refused to come, he sent his general Lu Guang with an army. The general successfully raided Kucha and captured Kumarajiva.

But Lu Guang declared himself a king and didn't let go of Kumarajiva. He kept him imprisoned for years.

After returning to Kucha (Xinjiang), he converted to Mahayana Buddhism as an adult. He got ordained as early as 20. Kumarajiva's fame spread as a great monk, debater, and teacher. 

So much that his fame reached China and the ears of Qin emperor Fu Jian in his capital Chang'an.

Kumarajiva was the son of Kumarayana, an Indian prince turned monk who went on to settle in the Kingdom of Kucha (current day Aksu Prefecture, Xinjiang, China). 

Kumarajiva was sent to Kashmir, India to study Buddhist scriptures at an young age. He's said to have mastered many.
